"""
Christ Layer — 2 Chronicles chapters 9–12
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-2chronicles-9-12.py

Key typological connections:
- Ch 9: Solomon's worldwide glory as type of Christ's universal reign and wisdom;
  Queen of Sheba (Gentile pilgrim) → the nations' eschatological journey to Christ;
  666 talents (v13) → Solomon's drift beyond Deut 17 limits; throne → Christ's throne;
  nations' tribute → Rev 21:26
- Ch 10: Kingdom divided — Rehoboam's harsh yoke vs. Christ's easy yoke (Matt 11:28-30);
  divine sovereignty in the hardening (v15 → Rom 9:17-18); rejected messengers → Matt 21:35
- Ch 11: Remnant from all tribes following faithful priests to Zion → the church gathered
  around the true High Priest; Shemaiah's restraining word → divine preservation
- Ch 12: kānaʿ (humble oneself) produces mitigation; gold → bronze substitution marks
  diminishing glory; lōʾ hēkîn libôʾ (did not set his heart) → Jer 31:33 new covenant heart
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRON2_CHRIST_9_12 = {
  "9": {
    "1": "<p>The Queen of Sheba&rsquo;s pilgrimage to Solomon with &ldquo;difficult questions&rdquo; (<em>ḥîḏôṯ</em>, riddles/hard sayings) is the paradigmatic Gentile encounter with divine wisdom in the Hebrew Bible. Jesus cites her as the eschatological witness against his generation: &ldquo;The queen of the South will rise at the judgment with the people of this generation and condemn them, because she came from the ends of the earth to hear Solomon&rsquo;s wisdom — and look, something greater than Solomon is here&rdquo; (Matt 12:42; Luke 11:31). Her journey from the ends of the earth prefigures the nations&rsquo; eschatological ingathering to the one who is wisdom incarnate (1 Cor 1:30; Col 2:3).</p>",
    "2": "<p>Solomon answered all her questions — &ldquo;nothing was hidden from Solomon that he could not explain to her.&rdquo; The comprehensiveness of Solomon&rsquo;s wisdom-answers is a shadow of the one in whom &ldquo;all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge are hidden&rdquo; (Col 2:3). When the disciples ask Jesus about the destruction of the temple (Matt 24:3), about the greatest commandment (Matt 22:36), about the resurrection (Matt 22:23-32), about taxes (Matt 22:15-22) — no question exceeds his capacity to answer; every question becomes an occasion for revelation beyond what the questioner anticipated.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The queen observes not only Solomon&rsquo;s wisdom but its material expressions — the palace, the organizational systems, the service. In Chronicles, wisdom always has concrete institutional form: the right organization of temple service, royal administration, and architectural beauty. Christ&rsquo;s wisdom similarly has concrete form in the church&rsquo;s ordered life (1 Cor 12-14; Eph 4:11-16), the community that embodies his wisdom before the powers (Eph 3:10).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The full vision of Solomonic glory — table, officials, attendants, cupbearers, the ascent to the temple — overwhelms the queen; &ldquo;there was no more breath in her&rdquo; (the Hebrew idiom for being overcome). The complete integration of feasting, service, and worship in Solomon&rsquo;s court is the type of the eschatological feast where the Lord serves his own at table (Luke 12:37: &ldquo;he will dress himself to serve, will have them recline at the table and will come and wait on them&rdquo;) — the king who is also servant, the host who is also butler.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The queen confesses that the report was true and that she did not believe it until she saw it. The pattern of hearing-then-seeing, of testimony preceding experience, runs through Scripture: the Samaritans say to the woman, &ldquo;We no longer believe just because of what you said; now we have heard for ourselves&rdquo; (John 4:42). The queen&rsquo;s journey from report to presence is the structure of faith — and of the gospel that moves from testimony to encounter.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&ldquo;Not even half of your great wisdom was reported to me.&rdquo; The excess of reality over testimony is a structural principle of Christ&rsquo;s glory: &ldquo;Eye has not seen, ear has not heard, and the heart of man has not imagined, what God has prepared for those who love him&rdquo; (1 Cor 2:9). Every account of Christ&rsquo;s glory in Scripture falls short of the reality (Rev 1:17: John falls as though dead at the sight of the risen Christ); the queen&rsquo;s confession that she underestimated Solomon foreshadows every believer&rsquo;s experience of the one greater than Solomon.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;How fortunate are your men, and how blessed are these servants of yours who stand before you continually.&rdquo; The beatitude for those who stand in Solomon&rsquo;s presence reflects the beatitude of worship — those who dwell in YHWH&rsquo;s presence are blessed (Ps 84:4: &ldquo;How blessed are those who dwell in your house, who are ever praising you&rdquo;). Christ pronounces his own version of this beatitude on those who witness what prophets and kings longed to see: &ldquo;Blessed are the eyes that see what you see&rdquo; (Luke 10:23). The servants standing before the king is the prototype of the church standing in the presence of the greater Solomon.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The queen&rsquo;s doxology: &ldquo;Blessed be the LORD your God, who has delighted in you and placed you on his throne as king for the LORD your God.&rdquo; A Gentile queen pronounces a blessing on YHWH through the king who represents him — and identifies the king&rsquo;s throne as YHWH&rsquo;s throne. This is the Chronicler&rsquo;s royal theology made explicit by a pagan: Solomon sits on &ldquo;the throne of YHWH&rdquo; (1 Chr 29:23) as YHWH&rsquo;s representative. The queen unwittingly confesses what the NT states directly: the Father has placed the Son on the throne because of his delight in him (Matt 3:17: &ldquo;This is my beloved Son, in whom I am well pleased&rdquo;; Heb 1:8: &ldquo;Your throne, O God, is forever&rdquo;).</p>",
    "9": "<p>The queen&rsquo;s gifts: 120 talents of gold, enormous spices, precious stones. Gentile royalty bringing gold and spices to the king who sits on YHWH&rsquo;s throne is the template the Magi fulfill (Matt 2:11: &ldquo;they offered him gifts of gold, frankincense, and myrrh&rdquo;). The Magi&rsquo;s gifts are not arbitrary; they follow the pattern of the Queen of Sheba&rsquo;s tribute and the royal Psalm&rsquo;s vision (Ps 72:10-11: &ldquo;The kings of Tarshish and the coasts will render tribute; the kings of Sheba and Seba will bring gifts; all kings will bow down to him&rdquo;). The queen&rsquo;s gold is the type; the Magi&rsquo;s gold is the partial fulfillment; the ingathering of nations to Christ is the completion.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The servants of Huram and Solomon bring gold from Ophir along with algum wood and precious stones — a joint Tyrian-Israelite commercial operation bringing building materials and luxury goods. The collaboration of Gentile craft and Israelite worship direction to build YHWH&rsquo;s house prefigures the grafting of the Gentiles into the one olive tree (Rom 11:17-24), the joint participation of Jew and Gentile in building the spiritual house (Eph 2:19-22: &ldquo;you are being built together into a dwelling place of God in the Spirit&rdquo;).</p>",
    "11": "<p>The algum wood is used for steps in the temple and for harps and lyres — worship infrastructure. The instruments of praise are built from the same wood as the temple&rsquo;s structure; music is architecturally integrated into the house. In the new creation, the new song (Rev 5:9; 14:3) is similarly inseparable from the temple — the whole city is the temple and the whole temple resounds with the song of the redeemed from every nation.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Solomon gives the queen &ldquo;everything she desired and asked for, over and above what she had brought to the king.&rdquo; The divine economy of the covenant is not equivalent exchange but superabundance: what the queen brings is returned with excess. This is the pattern of grace: &ldquo;With the measure you use, it will be measured to you — and more will be added to you&rdquo; (Mark 4:24); &ldquo;He who did not spare his own Son but gave him up for us all, how will he not also along with him graciously give us all things?&rdquo; (Rom 8:32). The return exceeds the gift.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Solomon&rsquo;s annual gold income: 666 talents. The number is not symbolic in Chronicles; it records Solomon&rsquo;s actual revenue. But the accumulation of gold beyond the limit set in Deut 17:17 (&ldquo;he must not accumulate large amounts of silver and gold for himself&rdquo;) marks Solomon&rsquo;s drift from the Torah&rsquo;s vision of kingship. The one who accumulates wealth without limit becomes a king for himself rather than for the LORD. Revelation&rsquo;s use of 666 for the beast (Rev 13:18) may draw on this association of unlimited wealth-accumulation with idolatrous power. Christ explicitly refuses this path: &ldquo;The Son of Man has nowhere to lay his head&rdquo; (Matt 8:20).</p>",
    "14": "<p>Additional income from merchants, traders, and tributary kings — the economic network of Solomon&rsquo;s empire. The universal tribute paid to Solomon (all the kings of Arabia, regional governors) is the earthly shadow of the eschatological tribute to the king of kings: &ldquo;The nations will walk by its light, and the kings of the earth will bring their glory into it&rdquo; (Rev 21:24). But Solomon&rsquo;s tribute is coercive taxation; Christ&rsquo;s tribute is the free gift of redeemed nations laying down their glory before the Lamb.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Two hundred large shields of hammered gold — display weapons never intended for battlefield use, hung in the House of the Forest of Lebanon. They represent Solomon&rsquo;s wealth-as-glory: gold armor signals that he has transcended the need for iron. But this glory is vulnerable, as ch 12 demonstrates when Shishak takes them and Rehoboam replaces them with bronze. Christ&rsquo;s glory is not the kind that can be stripped: &ldquo;the glory that I had with you before the world existed&rdquo; (John 17:5) is not material display but the eternal love between Father and Son.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Three hundred smaller shields of gold hung in the House of the Forest. The armory of gold shields is the visible statement of a king so secure that his weapons need never leave their display case. The contrast with Rehoboam&rsquo;s bronze shields (12:10) maps the dynasty&rsquo;s trajectory: from gold to bronze is a declension from Solomonic glory toward judgment. Only in Christ is the Solomonic glory not only restored but surpassed — the true king does not replace gold with bronze but gives himself as the treasure that rust cannot touch (Matt 6:19-21).</p>",
    "17": "<p>The great ivory throne overlaid with pure gold — the most elaborate throne description in the Hebrew Bible. Ivory (elephant tusk) and gold together signal maximum luxury and prestige. Solomon&rsquo;s throne is the earthly manifestation of the divine throne; 1 Chr 29:23 calls it &ldquo;the throne of YHWH.&rdquo; The elaborateness of the throne points forward to the divine throne in Revelation: &ldquo;The one seated on it had the appearance of jasper and carnelian; a rainbow that looked like an emerald surrounded the throne&rdquo; (Rev 4:3). Solomon&rsquo;s throne is built with human materials; the divine throne exceeds all human construction.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Six steps up to the throne with a gold footstool — the king ascends six steps to reach his seat, with lions at each level. The footstool of the king is a significant royal image; YHWH himself declares: &ldquo;Heaven is my throne and the earth is my footstool&rdquo; (Isa 66:1; Acts 7:49). Psalm 110:1 — the most-quoted OT verse in the NT — declares: &ldquo;The LORD says to my Lord: Sit at my right hand, until I make your enemies your footstool.&rdquo; Solomon&rsquo;s footstool is the earthly symbol of the cosmic sovereignty that the Son exercises from the Father&rsquo;s right hand.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Twelve lions on the six steps — one at each side of each step. The number twelve and the lion imagery together are Christological coordinates: the tribe of Judah is the lion (Gen 49:9; Rev 5:5: &ldquo;the Lion of the tribe of Judah has triumphed&rdquo;). Twelve lions flanking Solomon&rsquo;s ascent to the throne prefigure the twelve apostles who will &ldquo;sit on twelve thrones judging the twelve tribes of Israel&rdquo; (Matt 19:28) when the true Davidic king assumes his throne. &ldquo;Nothing like it existed in any other kingdom&rdquo; — the throne of the greater Solomon will likewise be incomparable (Rev 21:22-23).</p>",
    "20": "<p>All of Solomon&rsquo;s drinking vessels were gold — nothing of silver because silver &ldquo;was not considered valuable in Solomon&rsquo;s days.&rdquo; The banquet table of pure gold is the type of the eschatological feast: &ldquo;I will not drink again of the fruit of the vine until the kingdom of God comes&rdquo; (Luke 22:18). The wedding supper of the Lamb (Rev 19:9) will be the feast for which Solomon&rsquo;s golden banquet hall was a distant preparation — a feast not of Solomon&rsquo;s accumulated wealth but of Christ&rsquo;s self-giving.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The Tarshish fleet returning every three years with gold, silver, ivory, apes, and peacocks — exotic tribute from the far west. The three-year rhythm and the catalogue of marvels (the rare animals especially) communicate that Solomon&rsquo;s reach extends to the ends of the earth. Isaiah&rsquo;s eschatological vision uses the same Tarshish imagery: &ldquo;For the coastlands will look for me, and the ships of Tarshish first, to bring your sons from far away&rdquo; (Isa 60:9). The ships that bring tribute to Solomon become the ships that bring the children of God home in the eschatological ingathering.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&ldquo;King Solomon surpassed all the kings of the earth in riches and wisdom.&rdquo; The superlative of Solomon&rsquo;s reign is the Chronicler&rsquo;s signal that this is a typological peak — the closest the Davidic monarchy came to the divine ideal. Yet even this superlative falls short: Christ is not merely the wisest king but wisdom itself (1 Cor 1:24, 30), not merely the richest king but the one through whom &ldquo;all things were created&rdquo; (Col 1:16). The superlative of Solomon points beyond itself to the one about whom &ldquo;His name will be called Wonderful Counselor&rdquo; (Isa 9:6).</p>",
    "23": "<p>&ldquo;All the kings of the earth sought audiences with Solomon to hear the wisdom God had placed in his heart.&rdquo; The universal pilgrimage of kings to wisdom — seeking Solomon — is the type of the universal mission of the church: rather than kings coming to Jerusalem, the disciples go to all nations (Matt 28:19), bringing wisdom that is greater than Solomon&rsquo;s. The direction reverses: instead of the world coming to Israel&rsquo;s capital, Israel&rsquo;s descendant sends his people to the world.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Annual tribute: silver, gold, clothing, myrrh, spices, horses, mules. Every year from every king — a perpetual tribute stream. The eschatological vision of Isa 60:5-6 echoes this: &ldquo;The wealth on the seas will be brought to you, to you the riches of the nations will come; caravans of camels will cover your land, young camels of Midian and Ephah... they will come bearing gold and incense and proclaiming the praise of the LORD.&rdquo; What kings brought to Solomon in silver and gold, the nations will bring to Christ in praise and worship.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Solomon&rsquo;s horses: four thousand stalls, twelve thousand horsemen. The Chronicler has already noted that Solomon&rsquo;s horses came from Egypt (1:16-17). Deuteronomy 17:16 explicitly warns the king: &ldquo;he must not acquire many horses for himself or make the people return to Egypt to get more.&rdquo; Solomon&rsquo;s military infrastructure thus represents a slow drift from the Torah&rsquo;s ideal of a king who trusts YHWH rather than military power. Christ specifically refuses the militarized messianism that horses symbolize (Rev 6:2; Zech 9:9: the king &ldquo;riding on a donkey, on a colt, the foal of a donkey&rdquo; — the deliberate anti-war animal).</p>",
    "26": "<p>Solomon&rsquo;s dominion &ldquo;over all the kings from the Euphrates River to the land of the Philistines and down to the border of Egypt&rdquo; — the territorial fulfillment of the Abrahamic covenant (Gen 15:18: &ldquo;from the river of Egypt to the great river, the Euphrates&rdquo;). This is the only moment in Israel&rsquo;s history when the Abrahamic land promise finds its maximum territorial expression. Christ&rsquo;s dominion exceeds even this: &ldquo;Ask of me, and I will make the nations your heritage, and the ends of the earth your possession&rdquo; (Ps 2:8) — the scope is not one region of the ancient Near East but the entire creation.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&ldquo;The king made silver as common in Jerusalem as stone.&rdquo; The abundance of Solomon&rsquo;s reign — where precious materials become ordinary — is the type of the new creation&rsquo;s abundance: &ldquo;The city was pure gold, like clear glass&rdquo; (Rev 21:18); &ldquo;the street of the city was pure gold&rdquo; (Rev 21:21). In the new Jerusalem, what was previously precious becomes the pavement — the economy of glory inverts all normal scarcity. Solomon glimpses this abundance but cannot sustain it; the new creation achieves it permanently.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Horses brought from Egypt and all other lands — the international horse trade feeding Solomon&rsquo;s military expansion, explicitly the Egypt-connection Deut 17:16 prohibits. The quiet accumulation of what was forbidden is the Chronicler&rsquo;s explanation for why Solomon&rsquo;s reign cannot be permanent. Christ, by contrast, builds his kingdom on the one thing that cannot be taken away — his own sacrificial obedience — rather than on the accumulation of prohibited power.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Three prophetic source citations: Nathan the prophet, the prophecy of Ahijah the Shilonite, the visions of Iddo the seer. Solomon&rsquo;s acts are preserved in prophetic witness, not merely royal annals. The Chronicler consistently grounds history in the prophetic word, not in political record-keeping alone — reflecting the biblical conviction that the prophets are the true historians, reading events in light of YHWH&rsquo;s word. Christ is the word to whom all the prophets bear witness (John 5:39; Luke 24:27).</p>",
    "30": "<p>Forty years over all Israel in Jerusalem — the typologically resonant number of full-generation completeness (forty years in the wilderness; forty days of Jesus&rsquo; testing in Matt 4:1-2). Solomon&rsquo;s forty-year reign represents a complete era: the golden age runs its full course and ends. Every human golden age ends; the reign of Christ alone has no end (Luke 1:33: &ldquo;of his kingdom there will be no end&rdquo;; Heb 1:8: &ldquo;Your throne, O God, is forever and ever&rdquo;).</p>",
    "31": "<p>Solomon &ldquo;rested with his ancestors and was buried in the city of David his father.&rdquo; The regnal burial formula marks the end of the golden age. Every great king dies; the dynasty continues but the person does not. The Chronicler&rsquo;s entire narrative leads to the king who does not merely &ldquo;rest with his ancestors&rdquo; but rises from death: &ldquo;For David, after he had served God&rsquo;s purpose in his own generation, fell asleep and was buried with his fathers... but the one whom God raised from the dead did not see decay&rdquo; (Acts 13:36-37). Solomon&rsquo;s burial in the city of David is the type that the empty tomb reverses.</p>"
  },
  "10": {
    "1": "<p>Rehoboam goes to Shechem — the ancient covenant city where Joshua had renewed the covenant (Josh 24:1-28) and where tribal politics were negotiated. The choice of Shechem rather than Jerusalem for the coronation assembly signals that northern Israel is making a claim: they will crown the next king on their terms, not simply receive the hereditary succession. The political theater of Shechem contrasts with the divine theater of the anointing at Hebron (1 Chr 11:1-3); what should be a covenant ceremony becomes a negotiation of power.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Jeroboam returns from Egypt where he had fled from Solomon (1 Kgs 11:40). Egypt is the place of slavery in Israel&rsquo;s memory; a king who flees to Egypt is using the tyrant&rsquo;s refuge. Jeroboam&rsquo;s return from Egypt to lead Israel&rsquo;s resistance against Solomon&rsquo;s son echoes the pattern of Israel calling on Egypt for help against Assyria — turning to the house of slavery for political salvation rather than to YHWH.</p>",
    "3": "<p>All Israel sends for Jeroboam — he arrives as the people&rsquo;s representative against the dynasty. The scene sets up the pivotal confrontation: the heir of David vs. the popular champion of the north. The Chronicler frames this as a moment of covenant decision: will the king hear his people&rsquo;s voice or impose his father&rsquo;s will? The outcome is already known; the question is whether the king&rsquo;s heart will be open or closed.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The people&rsquo;s complaint: &ldquo;Your father made our yoke heavy. Now lighten the burden and the heavy yoke he imposed on us.&rdquo; The yoke (<em>ʿōl</em>) and burden (<em>ʿăḇōḏāh</em>, service/labor) language is the vocabulary of Egypt: Israel had cried out from their <em>ʿăḇōḏāh</em> in Egypt (Exod 1:13-14; 2:23). Solomon&rsquo;s forced labor has recreated Egyptian conditions within the covenant people. Jesus addresses this directly: &ldquo;Come to me, all who are weary and burdened (<em>pephor­tis­me­noi</em>), and I will give you rest. Take my yoke (<em>zygon</em>) upon you and learn from me, for I am gentle and humble in heart, and you will find rest for your souls. For my yoke is easy and my burden is light&rdquo; (Matt 11:28-30). Rehoboam&rsquo;s answer to the people&rsquo;s plea for a lighter yoke will be the heaviest possible; Christ&rsquo;s answer is the lightest.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;Come back to me in three days.&rdquo; The three-day delay — the time Rehoboam takes to deliberate — is the same duration of crisis resolution throughout Scripture: three days of darkness in Egypt (Exod 10:22), Jonah in the fish, Jesus in the tomb. The three-day interval here is a deliberative pause that becomes catastrophic when the king makes the wrong decision. The three days of Christ&rsquo;s burial are the interval of apparent defeat that becomes the pivot of history.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Rehoboam consults the elders who served Solomon — the voice of accumulated wisdom. Their counsel (v7: &ldquo;speak kindly to them&rdquo;) represents the politics of covenant-generosity: a king who serves his people earns loyal service. This is the vision of kingship that David embodied and Solomon modeled at the beginning of his reign. It is also the vision Christ embodies as the servant-king: &ldquo;Whoever wants to become great among you must be your servant&rdquo; (Matt 20:26-28).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The elders&rsquo; advice: &ldquo;If you will be generous to this people, please them, and speak kindly to them, they will be your servants forever.&rdquo; The servanthood paradox — kindness produces loyal service more effectively than coercion — is the political expression of the gospel dynamic. Christ demonstrates this: the servant-king who washes his disciples&rsquo; feet (John 13:14-15) creates loyalty that persecution cannot destroy. Rehoboam refuses this wisdom; it will be expressed instead by the one greater than Solomon who comes &ldquo;not to be served but to serve&rdquo; (Matt 20:28).</p>",
    "8": "<p>Rehoboam abandons the elders&rsquo; counsel and turns to the young men who grew up with him. The rejection of wisdom in favor of peer-group validation is the opposite of Solomon&rsquo;s beginning (when he asked for wisdom, 1:10). The son who inherited the greatest gift Israel ever received — a father&rsquo;s God-given wisdom — chooses instead the counsel of his friends. This is the story of Israel: &ldquo;They exchanged the glory of God for images&rdquo; (Rom 1:23); the wisdom available in the Torah is exchanged for human expediency.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Rehoboam asks his companions: &ldquo;What do you advise we answer these people?&rdquo; The framing is entirely political — &ldquo;What do we tell them?&rdquo; not &ldquo;What is right?&rdquo; or &ldquo;What does the LORD require?&rdquo; The absence of any reference to seeking the LORD (the Chronicler&rsquo;s key diagnostic verb <em>dāraš</em>) is the implicit condemnation: Rehoboam makes the most consequential decision of his reign without consulting YHWH. Jesus never made a consequential decision without prayer (Luke 6:12; 22:41-44).</p>",
    "10": "<p>The young men advise maximum harshness: &ldquo;My little finger is thicker than my father&rsquo;s waist.&rdquo; The language of bodily supremacy (my smallest part exceeds your greatest) is the rhetoric of domination. This is the anti-wisdom of imperial power: escalate, never concede, project invincibility. The beast in Revelation operates by the same rhetoric — the boastful mouth speaking great things (Rev 13:5-6). Christ deconstructs this entire framework: &ldquo;The kings of the Gentiles lord it over them... but not so with you&rdquo; (Luke 22:25-26).</p>",
    "11": "<p>&ldquo;Where my father burdened you with a heavy yoke, I will make it even heavier. My father punished you with whips; I will use scorpions.&rdquo; The escalation from whip to scorpion (barbed scourge) is the rhetoric of terror-governance. In the passion narrative, both instruments appear: Jesus is scourged (Mark 15:15) by the political power that does what Rehoboam threatened — using violence to maintain control. Christ submits to the scorpion-equivalent so that his people need never bear it (Isa 53:5: &ldquo;the punishment that brought us peace was on him&rdquo;).</p>",
    "12": "<p>The people return on the third day as commanded and Rehoboam answers harshly. The king&rsquo;s harsh word (<em>qāšāh</em>) is the vocabulary of Egypt again: &ldquo;the harsh service (<em>bᵉ&shy;ḵōl-ʿăḇōḏāh qāšāh</em>) with which they made them work&rdquo; (Exod 1:14). Rehoboam literally re-creates Pharaoh. The NT contrast is explicit: &ldquo;you did not receive the spirit of slavery to fall back into fear&rdquo; (Rom 8:15); Christ redeems from the harsh-word king&rsquo;s dominion into the kingdom of the servant-king.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Rehoboam answers harshly and rejects the elders&rsquo; advice — two parallel statements of double rejection. The structural pattern: the king refuses good counsel from his father&rsquo;s advisers and chooses bad counsel from his own companions. In the NT, Jesus&rsquo; hearers repeatedly face the same structural choice: receive the word of the one greater than Solomon, or fall back on their own reasoning. &ldquo;Everyone who hears these words of mine and puts them into practice is like a wise man who built his house on the rock&rdquo; (Matt 7:24).</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;My father made your yoke heavy; I will make it even heavier. My father punished you with whips; I will use scorpions.&rdquo; The full harshness speech is delivered. This is the human king at his worst: the covenant relationship reduced to extraction and control. The contrast with the true king is absolute — Christ says &ldquo;my yoke is easy&rdquo; where Rehoboam says his yoke will be heavier; Christ comes &ldquo;not to be served but to serve&rdquo; where Rehoboam demands maximum service; Christ gives his life where Rehoboam threatens lives.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;The king would not listen to the people, for this turn of events was from God, so that the LORD could fulfill his word which he had spoken through Ahijah the Shilonite to Jeroboam.&rdquo; The Chronicler inserts the divine sovereignty statement: behind Rehoboam&rsquo;s foolishness is YHWH&rsquo;s providential purpose. The hardening of Pharaoh (Exod 7-10) has its analogue here: the king&rsquo;s hardness serves the divine plan. Paul applies the same logic to Israel&rsquo;s partial hardening: &ldquo;God gave them a spirit of stupor&rdquo; (Rom 11:8) so that the Gentiles might be grafted in (Rom 11:11-12). The catastrophe of division is simultaneously a fulfillment of prophecy and an opening for YHWH&rsquo;s wider purpose.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;What share do we have in David? We have no portion in the son of Jesse. Every man to your tents, Israel! Now look after your own house, David!&rdquo; The repudiation of the Davidic covenant — &ldquo;we have no share in David&rdquo; — echoes Sheba&rsquo;s identical cry in 2 Sam 20:1. Those who say &ldquo;we have no share in David&rdquo; are choosing the kingdom that will eventually be destroyed over the Davidic line through which the eternal king will come. John 1:11 captures the deepest echo: &ldquo;he came to his own, and his own people did not receive him.&rdquo;</p>",
    "17": "<p>Rehoboam reigns over the Israelites &ldquo;living in the towns of Judah&rdquo; — his kingdom immediately contracts to its minimum. The dynasty that ruled from Egypt to the Euphrates (9:26) now holds only Judah and Benjamin. The contraction is the beginning of the long diminishment that ends in the Babylonian exile. Only the resurrection of the Davidic kingdom in Christ — with dominion over the ends of the earth (Ps 2:8; Acts 13:33-34) — reverses this contraction.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Hadoram the labor supervisor is stoned to death by the Israelites — the king&rsquo;s agent killed by the people in revolt. Rehoboam flees in his chariot. The killing of the king&rsquo;s representative prefigures the pattern in Jesus&rsquo; parable: &ldquo;The tenants seized his servants; they beat one, killed another, and stoned a third&rdquo; (Matt 21:35); &ldquo;They will kill the Son of Man&rdquo; (Matt 20:18). The rejection escalates from refusing the word (v14) to killing the agent (v18) — the same escalation Jesus narrates in the parable of the wicked tenants.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&ldquo;Israel has been in rebellion against the house of David to this day.&rdquo; The Chronicler closes the chapter with a verdict that spans centuries: the division initiated at Shechem is a permanent state of rebellion. The phrase &ldquo;to this day&rdquo; (<em>ʿad hayyôm hazzeh</em>) indicates the ongoing condition at the time of writing — the division is not a temporary crisis but a lasting rupture. Only the gathering of all Israel under the one shepherd (Ezek 37:22-24: &ldquo;my servant David will be king over them&rdquo;; John 10:16: &ldquo;there will be one flock and one shepherd&rdquo;) will end this &ldquo;to this day.&rdquo;</p>"
  },
  "11": {
    "1": "<p>Rehoboam mobilizes 180,000 select warriors from Judah and Benjamin to fight against Israel and recover the kingdom. The military response to political rupture — attempting to reunify by force — is the instinct of every human king. It is also precisely what YHWH&rsquo;s word will forbid (v4). The mustering of armies to force reunification contrasts with the one shepherd who gathers the scattered flock not by military force but by laying down his life: &ldquo;I will bring them out from the peoples and gather them from the countries&rdquo; (Ezek 34:13).</p>",
    "2": "<p>The word of YHWH comes to Shemaiah the man of God — the divine word interrupting human plans. The prophet appears at the exact moment when the armies are about to march; the word of YHWH is the restraining power that prevents civil war. This is divine preservation: the house of David is protected from its own destructive impulses by prophetic intervention. The NT equivalent is the restraining work of the Spirit (2 Thess 2:7) and the intercessory word of Christ (Heb 7:25).</p>",
    "3": "<p>Shemaiah addresses his word to &ldquo;all Israel in Judah and Benjamin&rdquo; — explicitly naming the southern remnant as &ldquo;all Israel.&rdquo; The Chronicler&rsquo;s ecclesiology is present here: the legitimate covenant community that maintains the temple, the Davidic king, and the Levitical priesthood is &ldquo;all Israel&rdquo; even when only two tribes remain. The partial is treated as the whole because it preserves the institutional forms of covenant life. The NT parallel: the church as &ldquo;the Israel of God&rdquo; (Gal 6:16), the remnant that is treated as the whole covenant people in Christ.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;This thing is from me&rdquo; (<em>mēʾittî nihyᵉtāh haddāḇār hazzeh</em>). YHWH takes ownership of the division: the splitting of the kingdom is his act of judgment, not merely a political accident. The obedience that follows — the armies go home — is an act of theological trust: the people accept that YHWH&rsquo;s purposes run through what looks like catastrophe. &ldquo;This thing is from me&rdquo; is the same confidence Paul expresses in Rom 8:28: &ldquo;in all things God works for the good of those who love him.&rdquo;</p>",
    "5": "<p>Rehoboam lives in Jerusalem and builds up defenses — turning inward after the failed military option. The fortification of Jerusalem and 15 southern cities reflects a defensive posture: the king who cannot expand his kingdom by force strengthens what he has. This is a diminished form of Solomon&rsquo;s universal reign but also an appropriate response to the new situation — stewardship of the smaller kingdom entrusted to him. The contrast with Christ: Jesus does not build defensive walls but sends his people out (Matt 28:19), expanding the kingdom not by fortification but by proclamation.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Bethlehem listed among Rehoboam&rsquo;s fortified cities — the city of David as a military installation. The Chronicler notes it without comment, but the NT reader cannot miss the irony: the city being fortified against political threat is the city where the ultimate Davidic heir will be born (Mic 5:2; Matt 2:1-6) to a family that is anything but military-powerful. Bethlehem is both a fortress and a birthplace; the combination of strength and vulnerability defines the Davidic line.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Beth-zur, Soco, Adullam — the hill country fortresses south and west of Jerusalem. Adullam especially resonates: it was the cave where David sheltered when Saul pursued him (1 Sam 22:1-2), where the marginal and the indebted gathered to him. The fortification of David&rsquo;s refuge cave as a military installation marks the distance between David&rsquo;s kingdom-in-exile and Rehoboam&rsquo;s defensive monarchy. The true Davidic heir will again welcome the marginal — &ldquo;blessed are the poor in spirit&rdquo; (Matt 5:3) — but as the beginning of the kingdom, not as a defensive strategy.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Gath, Mareshah, Ziph — Philistine territory and Judean heartland. The former Philistine stronghold Gath is being incorporated into Judah&rsquo;s defensive network. What was enemy territory under David&rsquo;s military dominance is now being held defensively. The contraction of Rehoboam&rsquo;s kingdom is visible in what cities he considers peripheral enough to need fortification — the borders have shrunk to the Judean core.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Adoraim, Lachish, Azekah — the major western approaches to Jerusalem. Lachish especially is the key western fortress that Sennacherib will besiege (32:9) and that appears repeatedly in military contexts. The defensive line Rehoboam creates is the same one that will eventually fall — these fortifications will not save Jerusalem in 701 or 586 BCE. The city that cannot be defended by walls will ultimately be protected only by YHWH (Ps 127:1: &ldquo;Unless the LORD watches over the city, the guards stand watch in vain&rdquo;).</p>",
    "10": "<p>Zorah and Aijalon — the northern edge of Judean territory, the sites of early Israelite battles (Judg 1:35; 1 Sam 14:31). By including these frontier cities, Rehoboam marks the boundary of what remains: the tribal inheritances of Judah and Benjamin. The contraction from Solomon&rsquo;s universal dominion to this tribal core is the history of failure that the Chronicler records — and that only the resurrection of the Davidic king will fully reverse.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Rehoboam reinforces strongholds, appoints commanders, and stockpiles food, olive oil, and wine. The provisions — the essential commodities — indicate preparation for siege. Olive oil and wine are also the substances of covenant life: oil for anointing (Ps 133:2) and wine for celebration (Ps 104:15) are now being stored as emergency supplies. The covenant goods become war materials. Christ, by contrast, uses bread and wine not for survival but for the new covenant feast (Luke 22:19-20).</p>",
    "12": "<p>Shields and spears stockpiled in every fortified city. The Chronicler closes the fortification list with military inventory — Judah and Benjamin are now a well-defended remnant. The survival of the remnant is the Chronicler&rsquo;s persistent concern: even in contraction, YHWH preserves a people for his covenant purposes. Paul cites Elijah&rsquo;s remnant as the model (Rom 11:4-5: &ldquo;I have reserved for myself seven thousand who have not bowed the knee to Baal. So too, at the present time there is a remnant chosen by grace&rdquo;).</p>",
    "13": "<p>Priests and Levites from throughout Israel align themselves with Rehoboam — a massive religious migration from north to south. The Levites &ldquo;left their pasturelands and property and came to Judah and Jerusalem, because Jeroboam and his sons had rejected them as priests of the LORD&rdquo; (v14). The priestly migration is the defining event of ch 11: the legitimate worship of YHWH, embodied in the Levitical priesthood, follows the Davidic king and the Jerusalem temple. This pattern will be repeated in the church: those who maintain legitimate worship and teaching separate from the institution of false religion.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The Levites leave their pastures (the Levitical cities given in Num 35 and Josh 21) and their landholdings and come to Judah. They abandon economic security and property ties to remain with the legitimate sanctuary. This is the same pattern Jesus describes: &ldquo;there is no one who has left house or brothers or sisters or mother or father or children or fields for my sake and for the gospel&rsquo;s sake, who will not receive a hundredfold now in this age&rdquo; (Mark 10:29-30). The Levitical migration for the sake of true worship prefigures the cost of discipleship.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Jeroboam appoints his own priests for the high places, the &ldquo;goat demons&rdquo; (<em>śᵉʿîrîm</em>, goat-idols; cf. Lev 17:7), and the golden calves. The counterfeit priesthood — self-appointed rather than divinely called, serving manufactured gods rather than YHWH — is the recurring danger. Paul warns: &ldquo;even if we or an angel from heaven should preach a gospel other than the one we preached to you, let them be under God&rsquo;s curse&rdquo; (Gal 1:8). The test of true priesthood is conformity to divine appointment and legitimate mediation, not popular approval or political utility.</p>",
    "16": "<p>From every tribe of Israel, those who had set their hearts (<em>nātenû ʾet-libbām</em>) to seek the LORD God of Israel followed the Levites to Jerusalem. The northern remnant within the northern kingdom — those who maintained true worship allegiance even after the division — make pilgrimage to Jerusalem. This is the Chronicler&rsquo;s vision of the true Israel: defined not by tribal geography but by the orientation of the heart toward YHWH. The gathering of the remnant from all twelve tribes prefigures the church as the gathered community of the truly seeking, assembled around the true High Priest (Heb 4:14-16).</p>",
    "17": "<p>These northern faithful strengthen the kingdom of Judah and support Rehoboam for three years — &ldquo;for three years they walked in the way of David and Solomon.&rdquo; The three-year period of faithfulness mirrors Solomon&rsquo;s early obedience before his heart turned (1 Kgs 11:1-4). Rehoboam too has a period of covenant faithfulness before the abandonment of ch 12. The pattern is one of promising beginnings followed by drift — the structural opposite of the one who &ldquo;learned obedience from what he suffered&rdquo; (Heb 5:8) and whose obedience was not seasonal but permanent.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Rehoboam&rsquo;s first wife Mahalath is the daughter of Jerimoth son of David — a granddaughter of David, connecting the royal line tightly to the Davidic genealogy. The Chronicler records the royal family details because the Davidic lineage matters: through this genealogical network the promise of the eternal throne (1 Chr 17:14) will be maintained. Each generation of the dynasty is a link in the chain that runs to the one who &ldquo;will be great and will be called the Son of the Most High, and the Lord God will give him the throne of his father David&rdquo; (Luke 1:32).</p>",
    "19": "<p>Three sons from Mahalath: Jeush, Shemariah, Zaham. The recording of sons is genealogical faithfulness — the Chronicler tracks the royal line carefully because the promise of 1 Chr 17 requires descendants. Each named son is a potential carrier of the Davidic covenant, though ultimately only one line will carry it to the virgin&rsquo;s child (Isa 7:14; Matt 1:1-16).</p>",
    "20": "<p>Maacah daughter of Absalom — the king&rsquo;s most beloved wife — bears him Abijah, who will succeed him. The beloved wife determines succession: Abijah becomes heir because of Rehoboam&rsquo;s love for his mother, not strict birth order (v22). Favoritism in succession produces instability; in Christ&rsquo;s kingdom, inheritance is not determined by favoritism but by adoption: &ldquo;he predestined us for adoption to himself as sons through Jesus Christ&rdquo; (Eph 1:5), and all adopted sons are equally heirs (Rom 8:17).</p>",
    "21": "<p>Rehoboam loves Maacah &ldquo;more than all his other wives and concubines&rdquo; — he had 18 wives and 60 concubines, fathering 28 sons and 60 daughters. The accumulation of wives explicitly violates Deut 17:17 (&ldquo;he must not take many wives, or his heart will be led astray&rdquo;). Solomon&rsquo;s 700 wives and 300 concubines (1 Kgs 11:3) established the precedent; Rehoboam&rsquo;s 78 women are a reduction but still a violation. The royal polygamy that the Torah warns against produces exactly the dynastic instability that follows: favoritism, rivalry, and divided succession.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Rehoboam designates Abijah as chief (<em>rōʾš</em>, head/prince) over his brothers — the beloved mother&rsquo;s son chosen as heir. The deliberate decision to make Abijah king-designate sets up a succession that will continue the Davidic line through this branch. The genealogical selection of each generation is the Chronicler&rsquo;s way of showing that the covenant promise is not automatic but specifically maintained through particular individuals whom YHWH watches over.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Rehoboam &ldquo;acted shrewdly&rdquo; by distributing his other sons throughout the districts, giving them provisions and finding wives for them. The political wisdom of distributing princes throughout the kingdom prevents court rivalries and ensures regional loyalty. This is the kind of prudent statecraft that belongs to earthly kingship but contrasts with Christ&rsquo;s method: Jesus sends his disciples not to strategic regional posts to consolidate power but as &ldquo;sheep among wolves&rdquo; (Matt 10:16), without provisions (Luke 10:4), to serve rather than govern.</p>"
  },
  "12": {
    "1": "<p>&ldquo;Once Rehoboam&rsquo;s rule was secure and he had grown strong, he abandoned the law of the LORD — and all Israel with him.&rdquo; The causal connection — security and strength lead to abandonment of Torah — is the fulfillment of Moses&rsquo; warning in Deut 8:10-14: &ldquo;When you have eaten and are satisfied... be careful that you do not forget the LORD your God.&rdquo; Prosperity is the most dangerous spiritual condition in the biblical narrative, more consistently producing apostasy than persecution does. Christ directly addresses this: &ldquo;what is highly valued among men is detestable in God&rsquo;s sight&rdquo; (Luke 16:15); &ldquo;how hard it is for those who have wealth to enter the kingdom of God&rdquo; (Luke 18:24).</p>",
    "2": "<p>In the fifth year of Rehoboam, Shishak king of Egypt attacks Jerusalem. The Shishak invasion (925 BCE; Shoshenq I, whose triumphal list at Karnak records the campaign) comes exactly at the moment of apostasy — the cause and effect are precisely correlated in the Chronicler&rsquo;s narrative. Egypt, the house of slavery from which YHWH redeemed Israel, returns to reclaim the covenant people who have abandoned their redeemer. The punishment perfectly matches the sin: those who forget YHWH&rsquo;s exodus are returned to their Egyptian overlords.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Shishak comes with an overwhelming force: Libyans, Sukkiim, and Cushites — a multicultural imperial army from Africa. The terrifying diversity of the invading force signals that all the nations can be mobilized against Israel when Israel abandons YHWH. The same dynamic runs in reverse in the NT: when Israel&rsquo;s Messiah is proclaimed, people &ldquo;from every nation under heaven&rdquo; (Acts 2:5) gather not to destroy but to hear the good news.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Shishak captures Judah&rsquo;s fortified cities — the very cities Rehoboam just built (11:5-12). The defensive infrastructure that took years to build falls immediately before the invader. The futility of fortifications without YHWH&rsquo;s protection is the point: &ldquo;Unless the LORD builds the house, the builders labor in vain; unless the LORD watches over the city, the guards stand watch in vain&rdquo; (Ps 127:1). The fortifications of 11:5-12 were built during the three years of faithfulness; they fail during the apostasy of v1.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Shemaiah the prophet comes to Rehoboam and the assembled leaders with the divine verdict: &ldquo;You abandoned me, so I have abandoned you (<em>gam-ʾănî ʿāzaḇtî ʾetḵem bᵉyad-šîšaq</em>) into the hand of Shishak.&rdquo; The divine mirroring of human action — your abandonment produces my abandonment — is the covenant lex talionis. This is not arbitrary punishment but structural consequence: the covenant relationship maintains itself through mutual faithfulness; when one party withdraws, the protection of the covenant is suspended. The gospel reverses this: Christ is not abandoned (Matt 28:20: &ldquo;I am with you always&rdquo;) even when his people are faithless (2 Tim 2:13: &ldquo;if we are faithless, he remains faithful&rdquo;).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The leaders of Judah and the king humble themselves (<em>wayyiḵānᵉʿû</em>) and confess: &ldquo;YHWH is just (<em>ṣaddîq YHWH</em>).&rdquo; The response to prophetic judgment is the Chronicler&rsquo;s decisive turning point: <em>kānaʿ</em> (humble oneself) is the key verb that determines whether a king experiences full judgment or mitigation. The confession &ldquo;YHWH is just&rdquo; is not merely an acknowledgment of his existence but a theological assent: we are wrong, he is right, his judgment is deserved. This is the posture Paul describes as the prerequisite for reconciliation: &ldquo;if we confess our sins, he is faithful and just to forgive us our sins&rdquo; (1 John 1:9).</p>",
    "7": "<p>When YHWH sees that they have humbled themselves, his word comes to Shemaiah: &ldquo;They have humbled themselves, so I will not destroy them, but I will grant them some escape (<em>mᵉʿaṭ</em>).&rdquo; The divine responsiveness to human humility — YHWH sees, and responds — is the structural core of covenant relationship. The mitigation is partial (&ldquo;some escape&rdquo;), not full restoration, because the humbling came after the apostasy rather than preventing it. The NT offers complete escape through preemptive substitution: Christ takes the full judgment so his people receive full deliverance rather than partial escape (2 Cor 5:21).</p>",
    "8": "<p>&ldquo;They will become his subjects so that they may learn the difference between serving me and serving the kingdoms of the lands.&rdquo; The purpose of discipline is comparative wisdom: the experience of foreign servitude will teach what YHWH&rsquo;s service provides by contrast. Jesus makes the same comparison explicit: &ldquo;For my yoke is easy and my burden is light&rdquo; (Matt 11:30) — the comparison is between Christ&rsquo;s service and the crushing burden of every other kind of service (the Torah as misapplied, sin, the fear of death, Heb 2:15). Judah needs to experience Shishak to appreciate YHWH; the reader is invited to understand the contrast without having to live it.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Shishak takes the treasures of the temple and the palace — including the gold shields Solomon had made (9:15-16). The removal of the gold shields from the House of the Forest of Lebanon is the Chronicler&rsquo;s most concrete symbol of Solomonic glory forfeited through apostasy. Every generation of apostasy strips something from the accumulated inheritance; what takes years to build is lost in an afternoon of conquest. The stripping of glory is reversed in Christ: &ldquo;the glory that you have given me I have given to them&rdquo; (John 17:22) — the Son distributes his own glory to his people rather than accumulating what is stripped from others.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Rehoboam replaces the gold shields with bronze shields — the most vivid image of diminished glory in Chronicles. The gold → bronze substitution maps the theological trajectory: the golden age of Solomon becomes the bronze age of his son. Bronze is not without value, but it is explicitly lesser than gold. Rehoboam maintains the form (shields in the House of the Forest) while the substance (gold) is gone. The substitution of form-without-substance for the genuine article is the Chronicler&rsquo;s warning against religion that maintains structures while losing the reality. Christ will restore not bronze for gold but the imperishable for the perishable (1 Cor 15:42-44).</p>",
    "11": "<p>The bronze shields are carried out whenever the king goes to the temple and then returned to the guardroom. The elaborate ceremony of bringing out and returning the substitute shields captures the pathos of the situation: the ritual continues, the guards march, the shields appear — but they are not what they were. The maintenance of liturgical form after the loss of genuine faithfulness is the Chronicler&rsquo;s persistent concern. Revelation describes the opposite condition: the church at Sardis has &ldquo;a reputation of being alive, but you are dead&rdquo; (Rev 3:1) — the bronze shield problem projected onto the NT church.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;Because he humbled himself, the LORD&rsquo;s anger turned from him and did not destroy him completely. Indeed, things went well in Judah.&rdquo; The partial humbling produces partial blessing — mitigation not transformation. The Chronicler&rsquo;s evaluation of Rehoboam is carefully calibrated: he is not condemned outright (as a king who never humbles himself would be) nor fully blessed (as David was). The middle category — partial faithfulness, partial judgment, partial restoration — is the realistic description of most human lives. Christ alone belongs to neither middle category; his obedience is complete and his blessing is entire (Phil 2:9-11).</p>",
    "13": "<p>Rehoboam reestablishes himself in Jerusalem at age 41, reigning 17 years. His mother was Naamah the Ammonite — a foreigner, which the Chronicler notes without comment but which explains the mixed religious environment of his upbringing. The mother&rsquo;s foreign origin is relevant: Solomon&rsquo;s foreign wives (1 Kgs 11:1-8) produced a son who never fully belonged to either world. The genealogical note reminds the reader that covenant faithfulness requires both heritage and personal choice; lineage from David does not guarantee the heart of David.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;He did evil because he did not set his heart (<em>lōʾ hēkîn libôʾ</em>) to seek the LORD.&rdquo; The causal diagnosis: the evil was rooted not in dramatic wickedness but in the unprepared heart — the heart that was not set toward YHWH as its primary orientation. The verb <em>kûn</em> (prepare, establish, set firmly) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s word for the heart&rsquo;s proper posture: David prepared (<em>hēkîn</em>) his heart (1 Chr 29:18); Solomon was charged to seek YHWH with a whole heart. Rehoboam&rsquo;s failure is the failure to prepare the heart — not gross immorality but insufficient orientation. The new covenant addresses this root: &ldquo;I will give you a new heart and put a new spirit in you&rdquo; (Ezek 36:26); the Holy Spirit establishes the heart toward God that the law could only command (Jer 31:33; Heb 8:10).</p>",
    "15": "<p>Source citations: the writings of Shemaiah the prophet and Iddo the seer — genealogical records. The regnal records trace both the acts (historical record) and the family history (genealogical continuity). Both matter to the Chronicler: the acts show the covenant response; the genealogy shows the preservation of the Davidic line. Chronicles is always simultaneously interested in what happened and who descended from whom, because the covenant promise runs through specific people in specific history.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;Rehoboam rested with his ancestors and was buried in the city of David.&rdquo; The death of every Davidic king is simultaneously a death and a continuation: the king dies, the dynasty persists. The burial in the city of David marks membership in the covenant line even for a king who failed to prepare his heart. Each king&rsquo;s death is a reminder that the eternal throne requires not a succession of mortal kings but the one immortal king: &ldquo;Jesus lives forever, he has a permanent priesthood; therefore he is able to save completely those who come to God through him&rdquo; (Heb 7:24-25). Rehoboam&rsquo;s burial is a rest awaiting the resurrection; Christ&rsquo;s burial was the three days before the permanent reign began.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', '2chronicles')
    merge_comm(existing, CHRON2_CHRIST_9_12)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', '2chronicles', existing)
    print('2 Chronicles 9-12 christ layer written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
